Explanations on global competitiveness.
In November, the World Economic Forum and the Center for International Development at Harvard University published the Global Competitiveness Report for the year 2001.
In a study encompassing 75 countries, Finland, the United States, and Canada occupy places one to three, while Nicaragua, Nigeria, and Zimbabwe form the tail end.
(All ranking lists are available at www.weforum.com.)
As the responsible leader of this annual study, I am often asked, what competitiveness actually means.
Is there also an economic competition among the countries, aside from the military competition?
Does it even make sense to say that Finland is more competitive than, for example, Germany or Italy?
In our report, competitiveness is precisely defined as the ability of a country to achieve sustainable economic growth in the medium term - within a period of five years.
This definition does not mean that the competitiveness of one country at the same time says something about the lack of competitiveness of another country.
With better political strategies, all countries of the Earth could achieve higher growth simultaneously.
Despite this, it is sensible to create a ranking list of countries in terms of their growth potential.
Every country is interested in finding out whether its political strategies and public institutions can keep up with those of other countries in terms of their ability to achieve sustainable economic growth.
In many respects, economic growth can be compared to a sports competition in which the gains of one country or region come at the expense of another country or region.
Countries, for example, compete for international mobile capital.
The more a country can gain from foreign direct investments, the less another country will get.
This becomes obvious when countries bid for a specific investment project.
If Intel plans a new semiconductor factory, various countries are invited to submit offers.
The competition for the contract is tough and often also involves tax breaks, infrastructure improvements, and even adjustments to study plans at the local technical university.
This year, we measured a country's competitiveness (growth capability) based on three broad criteria: (1) Technology, (2) public institutions, and (3) macroeconomic stability.
For each of these categories, we calculated key figures whose average values were calculated using a special method in order to then create a general growth and competition index.
The technology criterion relates to a country's ability to drive new developments and to utilize technologies that have been developed elsewhere.
Some countries like the US, Japan, Korea, Israel, and Sweden invest heavily in research and development, thereby achieving high values in the field of innovation.
Other countries such as Argentina and Brazil invest less in research and development and achieve little in terms of new products and procedures as a result.
Countries that are eager for innovation also enjoy a high standard of living due to these innovations.
In this area, the USA, Canada, and Finland occupy the first three places on the ranking list.
The criterion "public institutions" refers to the quality of administration.
Is corruption a widespread problem?
Are the courts incorruptible and impartial?
Can one trust that the government will comply with its commitments properly?
Countries with well-functioning public institutions achieve higher growth rates than countries with corrupt officials and degenerated judges.
High ethical standards promote economic performance.
In this regard, the North European countries are leading worldwide and Finland, Iceland, and Denmark are also at the top of the list.
Corruption is almost unknown in these countries.
Macroeconomic stability is defined by the absence of inflation, a balanced government budget, a realistic exchange rate of the national currency, the ability of businesses and the government to obtain loans on the capital market, and high trust that the government will meet its financial obligations.
We have learned in late 1990s in Asia that a macroeconomic crisis can negate economic growth, even if companies are internationally competitive.
The three leading countries in terms of macroeconomic stability are Singapore, Ireland, and Switzerland.
In our studies on competitiveness, we have noticed that the world economy can be divided into two categories of countries: those that are innovative and those that are not.
Only about 20 countries are actively involved in the development of new technologies.
In these countries, which count among the world's wealthiest, a superior system of technological innovations is considered a prerequisite for continued competitiveness.
Universities must be excellent, government laboratories should have world-class level, and the government and industry should invest heavily in research and development.
A key indicator for future growth in these economies is the proportion of students who attend higher schools and universities after completing compulsory schooling.
In the United States and Canada, this share amounts to 80%.
For countries not fond of innovation, technology is just as important, but most new technologies are imported from abroad and not developed in the country itself.
Some countries are skilled at importing new technologies, others less so.
In the past ten or fifteen years, a large part of the technology imports occurred within the framework of foreign direct investments.
American companies that heavily invested in Mexico or Taiwanese companies that invested in mainland China also brought new technologies that increased the efficiency of production in the target country's respective economy.
Therefore, it was certainly sensible for the affected countries to strive for these foreign investments with all their might: They bring not only capital, but also new technologies.
A strength and at the same time a weakness of our analysis of competitiveness is that it is medium-term oriented and does not focus on the next one to two years.
Our ranking lists are not suitable for evaluating short-term cyclical changes in an economy, but they do offer insight into the long-term prospects of major economies.
It is therefore an irony that many of the countries that will occupy the top places this year, such as the US or Singapore, are actually in a recession, while others, further down the ranking, such as China (rank 39), are not affected by the global recession.
The slowdown of the economy is partly linked to the terrorist attacks of September 11, but it is increasingly clear that the American economy and other economies connected with it through trade and production networks were already sliding into recession before September.
Despite this, we are of the opinion that this is a temporary cyclical downturn, and that the US will regain their ability to achieve a strong economic growth in the next five years.
